HEADWORD: Academical
<hw>Ac`a*dem"ic*al</hw>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>academicus</ets>:
cf. F. <ets>acad⟦eacute⟧migue</ets>. See <er>Academy</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Belonging to the school or philosophy of Plato; <as>as,
the <ex>Academic</ex> sect or philosophy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Belonging to an academy or other higher institution
of learning; scholarly; literary or classical, in distinction from
scientific.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Academic</xex> courses.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Warburton.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Academical</xex> study.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Berkeley.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Academic</ent>⟦br⟧
